{#
  nginx.conf.j2 — landing page + per-user redirect front door.

  Rendered by render_web_terminals() (Task 1.4, src/osprey/deployment/web_terminals/
  render.py) with a Jinja2 Environment that has autoescape=False — this emits nginx
  conf syntax, not HTML.

  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  TEMPLATE CONTRACT (variables render.py MUST supply — same object shapes as
  docker-compose.web.yml.j2; see that template's header for the full spec)
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

    nginx_port: int, required
    services: list[dict], required (may be empty)
      Same list docker-compose.web.yml.j2 consumes. Only `user` and `web` are
      used here — the artifact/ariel/lattice ports don't need a nginx route in
      Phase 1: the terminal UI is the only browser entry point reached from the
      landing page; the other three families are reached from links WITHIN the
      terminal UI once a user is on their own origin.

  Render output: this file is expected at `nginx/nginx.conf` (relative to the
  rendered docker-compose.web.yml.j2), matching the
  `./nginx/nginx.conf:/etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf:ro` mount in that
  template. The landing page itself (landing.html.j2's output) is expected
  alongside it at `nginx/landing.html`, matching that template's
  `./nginx/landing.html:ro` mount.

  THIS FILE IS A `server{}` FRAGMENT, NOT A COMPLETE MAIN CONFIG — no
  `events{}`/`http{}` wrapper, because `server`/`listen`/`location` are only
  valid nginx directives INSIDE an `http{}` block. It is deliberately mounted
  at `/etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf`, not `/etc/nginx/nginx.conf`: the base
  nginx image's own (untouched) main config already ships `events{}` and
  already `include`s `/etc/nginx/conf.d/*.conf` from inside its `http{}`
  block. Mounting this fragment at the main-config path instead would fail
  nginx's parse at startup ("server" directive is not allowed there) and the
  whole stack would never come up — validate any change to this file by
  running `nginx -t` with it mounted at the EXACT container path above
  (against the real base image, not wrapped in a hand-written http{} block),
  not just as a syntactically-standalone fragment.

  ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  WHY REDIRECTS, NOT REVERSE-PROXYING

  Every per-user app is host-networked (network_mode: host — see
  docker-compose.web.yml.j2's networking note) and binds its `web` port
  directly on the host (0.0.0.0); nginx cannot ALSO bind that same port —
  that's not a config choice, two processes can't share one host port. Real
  content-proxying under one shared path prefix at `nginx_port` would also be
  exactly the single-origin `/u/<user>/` scheme this module is told not to do
  in Phase 1 (that's reserved for a later, actual reverse-proxy design). So
  each per-user `location` below is a 302 REDIRECT to that user's own distinct
  origin (`http://<host>:<web_port>/`) — nginx never makes an outbound
  connection to the per-user app, it only tells the browser where to go next.
  `$host` (the Host header the browser sent nginx) is reused as the redirect
  target's host, so the same rendered config works unmodified behind whatever
  hostname or IP the deploy is actually reached at.

  0-user case: the loop below emits zero `location` blocks — the landing page
  (served at `/`) is the whole config, and it renders itself with an empty
  "users" group (see landing.html.j2's own emptiness handling). No
  `upstream {}` block is used in either case — redirects need none — so
  there's nothing that depends on `services` being non-empty to stay valid.
#}
server {
    listen {{ nginx_port }};
    listen [::]:{{ nginx_port }};
    server_name _;

    root /usr/share/nginx/html;

    location / {
        try_files /landing.html =404;
    }
{% for svc in services %}
{% if svc.user == "nginx" %}
  {# HARD FAIL: mirrors the same guard in docker-compose.web.yml.j2 — a user
     literally named "nginx" is reserved (see that template's header for why),
     and this template loops over the identical `services` list. #}
  {{ 1 / 0 }}
{% endif %}
    # Stable bookmark for {{ svc.user }} — redirects to their own origin.
    location = /{{ svc.user }} {
        return 302 http://$host:{{ svc.web }}/;
    }
{% endfor %}
}
